Our approach to accidental release prevention is full compliance with the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) standard and implementation of the ABS Consulting Process Safety Management Compliance program.  Key elements include: 



Process Safety Information - chemical hazards, process technology and equipment information is documented, maintained, and available to personnel; 



Process Hazards Analysis - process hazard analyses are conducted at least every five years to identify hazards of the process, review previous incidents with potential catastrophic consequences, engineering and administrative controls applicable to the hazard and their application to provide early warning of releases, consequences of failure of such controls,  source siting, human factors, and a qualitative evaluation of possible safety, health and environmental consequences as a result of failure of controls;



Operating Procedures - operating procedures provide detail on how to safely operate a process and are maintained up-to-date; 



Operator Training/Certification Program - the facility has a training and testing program that provides operators with the proper skills and knowledge prior to allowing them to independently operate a process; 



Maintenance Procedures - the plant has specific procedures for maintaining process equipment so that it operates safely; 



Maintenance Training - the facility trains personnel that will be performing routine or complex maintenance tasks on process equipment; 



Mechanical Integrity - Vessels and other process equipment are periodically tested and/or inspected, following recognized industry standards and/or governmental requirements, to ensure safe operation; 



Management of Change - The facility has a management system to ensure modified facilities and processes will be safe to operate; 



P

re-startup Review - reviews are conducted just prior to startup to ensure modified facilities and processes are safe for operation; 



Compliance Audits - independent third party audits are conducted at least every three years to verify procedures and practices are adequate and are being followed; 



Incident Investigations - the facility has a program to ensure accidents and incidents are properly investigated to determine the cause(s)and to implement corrective actions necessary to prevent the event from reoccurring: 



Employee Participation - the plant has a program to involve employees in prevention program elements: 



Hot Work Permits - the facility has a procedure to ensure welding, cutting and brazing are performed safely in areas where flammable or combustible material may be present;  



Contractors - the facility has a program to ensure contractors are properly trained and perform their work in compliance with the safety regulations.





The facility had one release that resulted in an injury during the last five years.  On 5/29/18, liquid chlorine line between the railcar unloading station and the vaporizer over-pressured.  This over-pressure resulted in the rupture disc bursting.  The rupture disc holder released approximately 92 pounds of chlorine into the atmosphere.  The escape of chlorine was through a tell-tale port in the rupture disc holder that did not have a plug in place at the time of operation of the rupture disc.  Twenty four (24) workers were given first aid at the nurse's station onsite, and one worker was treated at the hospital.  There were no off-site consequences or impacts as a result of this release.





